Package software.leonov.common.collect

Class TreeQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • software.leonov.common.collect.TreeQueue<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements held in this queue
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Queue<E>, BoundedQueue<E>, SortedCollection<E>
    public final class TreeQueue<E>
extends AbstractQueue<E>
implements SortedCollection<E>, BoundedQueue<E>, Cloneable, Serializable
    An optionally bounded priority Queue based on a modified Red-Black Tree. The elements of this queue are sorted according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Attempting to insert null elements will succeed if the Comparator supports null values. Inserting non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException. This queue uses the same general ordering rules as a PriorityQueue. The first element (the head) of this queue is considered to be the least element with respect to the specified ordering. A comparator is used (whether or not one is explicitly provided) to perform all element comparisons. Two elements which are deemed equal by the comparator's compare(E, E) method have equal priority from the standpoint of this queue. Elements with equal priority are sorted according to their insertion order.

    Besides the regular peek(), poll(), remove() operations specified in the Queue interface, this implementation provides additional peekLast(), pollLast(), removeLast() methods to examine the elements at the tail of the queue.

    If this queue is bounded and becomes full the offer(E) method behaves according to the following policy: if the element to be added has higher priority than the lowest priority element currently in the queue, the new element is added and the lowest priority element is removed; else the new element is rejected. The add(E) and addAll(Collection) operations will throw an IllegalStateException when the queue is full and a new element is rejected; as required by the contract of Queue.add(E).

    If the maximum size of this queue is not specified it will have an intrinsic capacity of Integer.MAX_VALUE elements.

    Bounded priority queues are useful when implementing n-best algorithms (e.g. finding the best n elements in an arbitrary collection).

    The iterator() and descendingIterator() methods return fail-fast iterators which are guaranteed to traverse the elements of the queue in ascending and descending priority order, respectively. Attempts to modify the elements in this queue at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

    This queue is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this queue concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    The underlying Red-Black Tree provides the following running time compared to a PriorityQueue (where n is the size of this queue and m is the size of the specified collection which is iterable in linear time):

      • create

        public static <E> TreeQueue<E> create​(Iterable<? extends E> elements)
        Creates a new unbounded TreeQueue containing the specified initial elements. If elements is an instance of SortedSet , PriorityQueue, MinMaxPriorityQueue, or SortedCollection this queue will be ordered according to the same ordering. Otherwise, this queue will be ordered according to the natural ordering of its elements.
        Parameters:
        elements - the collection whose elements are to be placed into the queue
        Returns:
        a new unbounded TreeQueue containing the elements of the specified collection
        Throws:
        ClassCastException - if elements of the specified collection cannot be compared to one another according to this queue's ordering
        NullPointerException - if any of the elements of the specified collection or the collection itself is null
